WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:04.880
Next to the Amazon River, there actually&nbsp;
is a second gigantic hydrographic system

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:11.040
with the Parana and Uruguay River draining&nbsp;
1/5th of the remaining continent. But about

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:16.640
280 kilometers before these rivers discharge&nbsp;
into the ocean, the riverbanks suddenly widen

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:21.840
into an enormous horn before the waters&nbsp;
finally flow into the Atlantic Ocean.

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:27.440
This funnel shaped indent into the South American&nbsp;
coastline is called the Rio de la Plata and it

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.240
looks very different to pretty much any other&nbsp;
river’s delta. So what actually happened here?

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:36.880
It all started with a wide geological fault&nbsp;
that formed during the breakup of Gondwana,

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:42.400
which gave the structural framework for the notch&nbsp;
in the continental shelf. As tectonic activity

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:47.040
further shaped the land of South America, much of&nbsp;
the continent's runoff was eventually redirected

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:52.240
into this originally 2 km deep depression and&nbsp;
millions of tons of loose sediments from the

00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:57.360
rivers then slowly got deposited within. By&nbsp;
now, the incoming sediments from the rivers

00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:02.800
and tidal forces from the Atlantic have found&nbsp;
an equilibrium, giving the Rio de la Plata a

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:08.640
gentle gradient from 2 to a 20 meter depth&nbsp;
at the transition with the Atlantic Ocean.

00:01:08.640 --> 00:01:13.520
Throughout these 280 kilometers, the Rio de&nbsp;
la Plata is separated into various zones with

00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:18.720
completely different habitats along the way. At&nbsp;
the mouth of the rivers, low salinity levels of

00:01:18.720 --> 00:01:24.560
around 2 PSU create a freshwater habitat which&nbsp;
slowly transitions to the mixed zone of brackish

00:01:24.560 --> 00:01:30.640
water, where a distinct vertical salinity gradient&nbsp;
rises from the sea floor to the water surface,

00:01:30.640 --> 00:01:34.800
and sediments are still heavily suspended&nbsp;
in the water, creating the characteristic

00:01:34.800 --> 00:01:39.520
orange and brown tints. After passing&nbsp;
the Uruguayan capital of Montevideo,

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:44.640
the water depth drops to its deepest level, the&nbsp;
funnel opens up to its maximum width, and the

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:50.720
tidal push raises the salinity level to over 10&nbsp;
times the level that is measured in Buenos Aires.

00:01:50.720 --> 00:01:55.440
Considering all of these characteristics, the Rio&nbsp;
de la Plata is actually quite the puzzle to the

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:59.840
scientific community which tries to make it fit&nbsp;
in with one of the standardized classifications

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:04.960
of hydrography. The most straightforward would&nbsp;
be calling it a river as the name suggests,

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:10.240
with the Spanish and Portuguese word Rio meaning&nbsp;
River in English. Looking at the overall geometry

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:14.960
and properties however it doesn’t really align&nbsp;
with what we would usually consider a river though.

00:02:14.960 --> 00:02:20.960
Alternatives are the terms Bay which is defined&nbsp;
as a broad inlet of the sea where the land curves

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:27.520
inwards, a Marginal Sea which is a semi-enclosed&nbsp;
body of water adjacent to, and widely open to the

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:33.840
ocean, or an estuary which is that area of a&nbsp;
river mouth which is affected by sea tides.

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:36.640
While every definition has&nbsp;
some fitting aspects to it,

00:02:36.640 --> 00:02:40.960
the debate probably won’t be settled anytime&nbsp;
soon but my personal favourite would be the

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:46.960
estuary since the brackish zone is such a&nbsp;
defining characteristic of the Rio de la Plata.

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:49.650
